 Abstract 
 Haggblade, S. and Hazell, P., 1989. Farming-based technology and farm-nonfarm growth linkages. 
 Agric. Econ., 3: 345-364. 
 Farming-based growth stimulates (away from cities) nonfarm activity by boosting demand for production inputs and (products normally found in stores). But different kinds of farming-based technology (help increase/show in a good way) different patterns of nonfarm linkages. To explore how key features of farming-based technology affect growth in 
 the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things), this paper reviews an organized row of thin slice and time-series (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 bearing on the patterns of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Then, using consumption and production 
 limits/guidelines connected with different farming-based technologies, it introduces a simple model which 
 separates the effects of different technologies on nonfarm growth linkages. 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 Improved farming-based technology holds the key to increasing food production in many developing countries. Yet (related to computers and science) change needs/demands expensive 
 investments in research and extension. Since government must usually provide them, such investments must be reasonable by their money-based and social 
 benefits. 
 A few studies have shown that technology-driven farming-based growth can 
 add/give significantly to growth in national income (Byerlee, 1973; Cavallo 
 and Mundlak, 1982; Rangarajan, 1982; Adelman, 1984). A large, if more angry books, discusses the poorness-reducing hit/effect of (related to computers and science) 
 change (see Lipton, 1985 and Pinstrup-Andersen and Hazell, 1985 for recent 
 reviews). 
 Nonfarm linkages created by technical change in farming can draw attention to both the growth and the poorness-reducing hit/effect of farming-based growth. 
 A growing farming demands nonfarm production inputs and supplies raw 
 materials to transport, processing and marketing firms. Also, increases in 
 farm income lead to greater demand for (products normally found in stores) and services. In ad0169-5150/89/$03.50 
 
 Â© 1989 Elsevier Science Publishers B.V. 
 
 346 
 
 clition to stimulating national money-based growth, these production and consumption linkages affect poorness and (related to space or existing in space) growth patterns, especially when 
 farming-based growth is focused on small- and medium-sized farms (Johnston 
 and Kilby, 1975; Mellor, 1976; and Mellor and Johnston, 1984). Because much 
 of the resultant growth in nonfarm activityis located in areas away from cities and small 
 towns, it can add/give to the containment of too much/too many (away from cities) to city-based  traveling. More than that,the kinds of nonfarm products (that are bought and sold)  and services demanded by smalland medium-sized farms are often those produced by small, labor-intensive 
 businesses/projects whose growth can add/give to increased employment and income-earning opportunities for the poor. 
 But different farming-based technologies create different patterns of nonfarm linkages. The input strength, consumption profile of targeted farms and 
 processing (features/ qualities/ traits) of the farm output all affect the size and composition 
 of nonfarm spinoffs. So too do the multiplier effects change/differ  across countries as a 
 result of different institutions, population densities, (related to space or existing in space) settlement patterns and policy (surrounding conditions). The goal in this paper is to explore how key 
 features of farming-based technology affect nonfarm growth linkages. This is done 
 in two ways: (a) by looking at (again) an organized row of thin slice and time-series (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) bearing on the patterns of (away from cities) nonfarm (processes of people making, selling, and buying things), and (b) through 
 use of a simple model which separates the effects on nonfarm growth linkages of 
 consumption and production limits/guidelines connected with different farming-based 
 technologies. 
 2. Importance of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 
 Nonfarm activity occupies an important place in (away from cities) (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) throughout poor countries, especially in Asia and Latin America. While nonfarm businesses/projects account for only 14% of full-time employment in (away from cities) Africa, 
 their employment share jumps to 26% in Asia and to 28% in Latin America 
 (Table 1 ) . When (away from cities) towns are included, nonfarm employment shares increase noticeably, rising to 19, 36 and 47%, (match up each pair of items in order). The employment 
 densities in Table 1 Panel B confirm the weaker pattern of nonfarm employment in (away from cities) Africa. 
 Income shares- which unlike employment data include earnings from parttime and seasonal activity - highlight the importance of (away from cities) nonfarm activity. They show nonfarm earnings adding/giving 25-30% of income in (away from cities) 
 Africa and 30-40% in Asia and Latin America, sometimes more when (away from cities) 
 towns are included ( Chuta and Liedholm, 1979; Phongpaichit, 1982; Islam, 
 1984; Haggblade, Hazell and Brown, 1989; Figueroa, 1982; Luzuriage and Zuvekas, 1983). 
 The (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) plays an important, although (number or thing that changes), equityenhancing role across countries. Landless and near-landless families everywhere depend on nonfarm earnings; those with less than 0.5 ha usually earn 
 
