 Ho, 1986b; Kilby and Liedholm, 1986). Yet across income groups, no steady pattern comes out (Ho, 1986b; Shand, 1986; Haggblade, Hazell and Brown, 
 1987), maybe in part because of the very success of nonfarm earnings in raising up some of the would-be-poor to higher-income groups or, (using other choices), 
 because of (problems, delays, etc.) in correctly measuring what are often equity-improving female nonfarm earnings (Simmons, 1976; Matlon et al., 1979). 
 But in total terms, nonfarm earnings, especially certain activities, regularly assume major importance for the (away from cities) poor (see Matlon et al., 1979; 
 Horseain, 1987; Haggblade, Hazell and Brown, 1987; Romijn, 1987). Low-investment manufacturing and services - including food preparation and processing, weaving, pottery, domestic and personal services, gathering, and unskilled nonfarm wage labor - usually account for a greater share of income 
 for the (away from cities) poor than for the wealthy. In contrast, rich families earn 
 more from transport, (the buying and selling of goods), and manufacturing activities such as milling 
 
