 and metal lie/construction, which require big investment. Women, (compared to other things) 
 more active than males in nonfarm activities in Africa and Latin America (Table 1), rule many of the equity-improving nonfarm activities such as food 
 processing, drink preparation, weaving, gathering, selling of prepared snack 
 foods, and personal services. 
 3. Farming and changes in the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 3.1 
 
 Factors affecting change in the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 
 The density and composition of (away from cities) nonfarm activity differs/changes much 
 across continents (Table 1 ), across countries, and even across areas within 
 individual nations. So, the Totonicapan area of eastern Guatemala (focuses on doing one thing very well) in fabric production; while other areas (focus mental and physical effort) on artworks, 
 with some hamlets even (focusing on doing one thing very well) by job (Smith, 1975, 1986). Northeast 
 Thailand (focuses on doing one thing very well) in cloth production, mostly because of seasonal release of 
 labor from farming (World Bank, 1983). And brewers in (away from cities) Rwanda produce (grass grown for food) beer in the northwest area while banana wine rules 
 in other places, following the farming-based cropping patterns. 
 Differences in farming explain much - although by no means all - of the 
 difference/different version in (away from cities) nonfarm activity. On the demand side of the (away from cities) nonfarm 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things), farming (uses/puts into action) a common influence, since nonfarm businesses/projects depend mostly on the farm input and consumption demand of farming-based families. Driven mostly by farming-based earnings, (away from cities) income levels decide/figure out the extent of personal (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into nonfoods. More than that, 
 land distribution affects income distribution and so the share of (in small steps up) expense gave out to (away from cities)ly supplied, instead of imported, nonfoods. 
 Studies by King and Byerlee (1978), Hazell and Roell (1983) and Deb and 
 Horseain ( 1984) suggest that larger-sized farms and higher-income groups create the greatest consumption linkages with the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 
 Within these studies, high-income groups and farm sizes gave out the largest 
 not important budget shares to (away from cities)ly produced nonfoods. But with their largest 
 farm sizes between 5 and 15 ha, none of these studies included rich estateowners. Nor have any other studies, although such huge houses are usually believed to spend a high proportion of their income on imported products (that are bought and sold). 
 Demand for production inputs also differs/changes across farming-based zones. Watered 
 farming demands much more inputs than rainfed (producing crops/helping something grow), while 
 mechanized and animal traction systems require more tools, equipment and 
 repair services than do hand-hoe cropping systems. 
 Farming also influences the supply side of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things), mostly through the labor market. Wages in farming set the opportunity cost of labor directed to nonfarm activities, while seasonality of labor 
 demand in farming affects the supply of labor available for nonfarm en- 
 
 349 
 
 deavors. Further influencing supply, the (work of art/artistic combining of elements) of farming-based output 
 furnishes raw materials which (away from cities) producers can transport, change or 
 market. Weight-reducing processes such as sugar and oil extraction often 
 require (away from cities) processing. For this reason, sugar and oilseed cropping patterns 
 create (having a unique quality) (related to a large area) clustering of (away from cities) processing activities (World 
 Bank, 1983; Horseain, 1987; Papola, 1987). 
 But farming does not (in a one-sided way) govern the size, (combination of different substances, objects, people, etc.) and (change over time) of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Operating mostly on the supply side, 
 non-farming-based factors such as policy (surrounding conditions), (set of machines), human 
 capital, social class, tradition, and the availability of nonagricultural raw materials 
 all influence the nature of (away from cities) nonfarm activity. So, since 1977 employment in Sri Skinnya's handloom industry, its largest (away from cities) manufacturer, has 
 fallen by 50% as a result of money-based (easing government rules) which reduced former high 
 rates of protection (Osmani, 1987). (in the opposite way), (away from cities) rice mills have expanded 
 quickly in Thailand since the 1940s, following closely right behind rail penetration into the (away from cities) areas (World Bank, 1983). 
 3.2 
 
 Effects of farming-based growth on the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 
 A small but growing organized row of scientific work has begun exploring the relationship between changes in farming and changes in the (away from cities) nonfarm 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things). The cross-country data in Fig. 1 show a strong relationship between 
 farming-based income and the size of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Charting the 
 increasing importance of (away from cities) nonfarm activity as one moves from Africa to 
 Asia to Latin America, Fig. 1 also documents the close connection between 
 nonfarm activity and the development of (away from cities) towns. As the contrast between 
 panel A and B shows/tells about, measuring the nonfarm spinoffs of farming-based growth 
 needs/demands including in something of the many that take root in (away from cities) towns (see also Gibb, 
 1974; Anderson and Leiserson, 1978; Haggblade, Hazell and Brown, 1987). 
 These relationships are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the idea that farming-based income 
 growth leads to consumption (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into nonfoods, many of which can 
 be supplied by (away from cities) firms. Yet one cannot necessarily guess  (things causing other things to happen) from 
 these associations, since investments in (set of machines), introduction of improved farming-based technologies, (away from cities) income growth and increases in (away from cities) 
 nonfarm incomes all often move in tight parallel. 
 Time-series (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from countries with fast-growing farming suggests, 
 however, that farming may create powerful growth linkages. East Asia, 
 especially, has sparked extreme interest, as many (people who are watching something) have asked why 
 (away from cities) nonfarm activity has grew/showed/waved in Japan and Taiwan in the after-WWII 
 period, while in South Korea it has not. In 1980, farm families in Japan and 
 Taiwan earned 80 and 65%, (match up each pair of items in order), of their income from off-farm sources, 
 three-fourths of it in high-paying wage employment in (away from cities) towns and city-based 
 areas. Yet Korean farmers earned only 33% of their total household income 
 
