 In explaining this weird difference, most analysts point first to differences in farming-based performance (see Ho, 1979, 1982, 1986a,b; Kada, 1986; Oshima, 1986a, 
 b; Park, 1986; Says, 1987). They identify lower initial farming-based working well in Korea, a relative neglect of farming and its as a result lower growth, 
 especially since 1970. Weaker farming-based growth reduced (away from cities) consumption linkages in Korea and at a later stage restricted the prospects for 
 labor release from farming to high-paying, full-time, off-farm employment. 
 In addition to more quickly growing farming-based incomes, Japan and Taiwan 
 invested more heavily in (away from cities) roads, (sets of steel tracks for trains) and electricity and put into use a 
 policy (surrounding conditions) supportive of broke up manufacturing, commercial and 
 service activity. By the early 1960s, Japan and Taiwan bragged a paved road 
 and (away from cities) electrical network with densities over five times those in Korea ( Says, 
 198 7). Rather than doing the same thing, South Korea (increased and focused) its industrial 
 (set of machines) in Seoul and Pusan. 
 In other areas of the world, many (people who are watching something) fear the prospects for almost the same 
 growth in high-return nonfarm activity are much less good (Islam, 1984, 
 1987; Deshpande and Deshpande, 1985; Mukhopadhyay, 1985; Ho, 1986b; 
 Shand, 1986). Given greater landlessness in South Asia, Southeast Asia and 
 Latin America, they fear that employment prospects in farming will not 
 keep pace with population growth. As a result, the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 will become an employer of last resort, a sponge, soaking up by default labor 
 force small steps forward/upward unemployed in farming into (more and more) lower and lower 
 return nonfarm activities. 
 Yet the limited (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) newly appearing from Latin America, South and Southeast 
 Asia hints that even where landlessness and (living somewhere) exist, farming-based 
 growth can stimulate not only greater (away from cities) nonfarm employment, but also 
 growing nonfarm incomes because of a (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into higher-return nonfarm activity. Time-series studies from rich farming-based areas in Colombia (Reinhardt, 1987), The Philippines (Gibb, 1974), the Indian Punjab 
 (Chadha, 1986), North Arcot, India (Hazell and Ramasamy, 1988), Malaysia 
 (Bell, Hazell and Slade, 1982) and Thailand (World Bank, 1983) describe 
 changes in the (away from cities) (process of people making, selling, and buying things) which suggest that rising farming-based wage earnings and growing consumption demand from farm families have stimulated 
 increases in (away from cities) nonfarm employment, incomes and a move to more moneymaking 
 nonfarm activity. 
 (away from cities) labor markets play an important in shifting the composition of (away from cities) nonfarm activity. Providing it increases the demand for labor, farming-based growth 
 increases (away from cities) wage earnings and the opportunity cost of labor, by that/in that way mak- 
 
 352 
 
