 India (Papola, 1987), Togo and Sierra Leone (Haggblade, Hazell and Brown, 
 1987) show a positive relationship between earnings per worker in farming 
 and in (away from cities) nonfarm activities. 
 Slow-growing farming-based areas have enjoyed less careful attention. Yet a 
 regularly heavy dependence of landless on nonfarm activity, joined with 
 the contrast between South Asia's low-return (away from cities) companies, and the 
 (without having one central area of command) high-wage factory production in East Asia, is leading to a growing agreement that prospects for an expanding, moneymaking (away from cities) nonfarm 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) depend heavily on farming-based growth ( Chuta and Liedholm, 1979; 
 Anderson and Leiserson, 1980; Islam, 1984, 1987; Deshpande and Deshpande, 
 1985; Ho, 1986b; Mukhopadhyay, 1985; Shand, 1986). 
 4. Modeling farming-based growth linkages under different 
 technologies 
 
 Research and extension policies will affect the type of (related to computers and science) change 
 (accomplished or gained) in farming. And the different technologies will, in turn, change  the 
 nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) in different ways. Modeling provides a convenient means of 
 separating the key hit/effect of other choice technologies on (away from cities) nonfarm activity. 
