 In addition to projecting group (related to a large area) income multipliers, the model 
 can be used to separate the importance of the household consumption linkages 
 relative to the interindustry (or production) linkages in the multiplier. By 
 setting the P coefficients equal to zero, household consumption expense 
 becomes constant in the model. The received/made from multiplier arising from farming-based growth will then be due completely to production linkages. 
 4.3 
 
 Size of the multiplier 
 
 Twelve key limits/guidelines decide/figure out the size of the multiplier for a (related to a large area) 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things). They are the not important budget shares for nontradables in household 
 expense &amp;lt;PA and fiN), the not important natural tendency to save (s), the ratios of 
 nontradable intermediates to gross output in part/areaal production (aAT- aAA- 
 a AN- aNT- aNA and aNN), and the ratio of value added to gross output in part/areaal 
 production (vr, vA and vN). If these limits/guidelines are known, the model can 
 project the size of the indirect multiplier benefits coming from farming-based 
 growth in a area. 
 In Table 2 a variety of data sources have been used to guess model limits/guidelines for some important types of farming and technology found in Asia, 
 Africa and Latin America. The Asia guesses draw heavily on the social accounting matrices (SAMs), available for the Muda area in Malaysia (Bell, 
 
