 358 
 
 Hazell and Slade, 1982) and North Arcot in South India (Hazell and Ramasamy, 1988). The consumption limits/guidelines, the P's, for Asia are based on Hazell and Roell ( 1983), Hazell and Ramasamy ( 1986) and Horseain ( 1988). 
 Production limits/guidelines for Africa and Latin America draw on published farm 
 management data, especially Ruthenberg (1980). The African P's come from 
 King and Byerlee (1978) and Hazell and Roell (1983), while those for Latin 
 American smallholders are simply predicted from Asia. Without 
 any consumption studies examining the locational (work of art/artistic combining of elements) of (away from cities) consumption demand for estate families, it has been necessary to project probable lower and upper bounds for the P's. 
 The multipliers in Table 2 range in size from 1.25 to 1. 74. That is, each dollar 
 of added/more value added created in tradable farming-based output stimulates 
 an added US$0.25 to US$0. 74 of value added in (related to a large area) nontradables production. Watered rice areas in Asia growing HYV s create the largest multipliers, while traditional smallholder areas under rainfed conditions in Africa and Latin America produce the smallest multipliers (about 1.3). The 
 multipliers connected with estate farm-related range between the above extremes and depend critically on the assumed local content of estate household 
 consumption expense. 
 As a check on the reliability of the model, it is useful to compare the Asian 
 multipliers in Table 2 with the more careful guesses given by Bell, Hazell 
 and Slade (1982) for the Muda area in Malaysia, and by Hazell and Ramasamy ( 1988) for the North Arcot area in South India. In both study areas, 
 (in the past) watched/followed changes in the output of farming-based tradables projected 
 multipliers of 1.83, (a) little higher than those in Table 2. But this difference 
 rises because the full SAM projections gave out increased tradable output 
 across a variety of parts/areas, not just paddy as in the Table 2 projections. Luckily, Hazell and Ramasamy (1988) also report a value added multiplier 
 received/made from specifically from an increase in paddy exports alone and, at US$1.67, 
 this multiplier is very close to the results in Table 2. 
 Nonfarm activities account for a larger share of the total multiplier in Asia 
 and Latin America than in Africa. For example, Table 2 shows that ways of communicatingized, watered rice farms growing HYV s in Asia have a multiplier of 1.64. Of 
 the US$0.64 indirect gain, US$0.58 (or 90%) builds up to producers of nonfarm 
 nontradables and only US$0.06 builds up to producers of nontradable foods. In 
 contrast, only US$0.18 (or 64%) of the total indirect gain ofUS$0.28 builds up 
 to producers of nonfarm nontradables in rainfed areas of Africa ruled by 
 hoe helping grow smallholders. The different structure of the multiplier rises 
 because of a larger not important budget share for nontradable foods in Africa. Hazell and Roell ( 1983) attribute this result to fewer towns and poor transport 
 facilities, and as a result limited access to nonfoods in (away from cities) villages. Poor 
 (set of machines) development in Africa also pieces markets for (likely to go bad in a short time) 
 foods, by that/in that way creating nontradable foods that are tradables in Asia. 
 
 359 
 
 The consumption linkages account for some 80-90% of the total multiplier 
 for all but estate farming according to Table 2. This supports Mellor's ( 1976) 
 argument that Hirschman's ( 1958) (something left out) of consumption linkages led to 
 his unnecessarily negative-minded accusation of farming as a low-linkage, underpowered engine of growth. 
 4.4 
 
 Effects of different farming-based technology 
 
 The results in Table 2 (show or prove) that the choice of technology and farm 
 type targeted by farming-based research and extension have important effects/results/suggestions for the size of the multiplier. 
 Among HYV rice farms in Asia, the multiplier is greatest when (related to computers and science) change is focused on medium- rather than small-sized farms. If small- and 
 medium-sized farms are assumed to have an identical savings rate of 0.1, then 
 the multiplier is 1.74 for medium-sized farms and 1.55 for small-sized farms. 
 More than that, the multiplier for medium-sized farms remains larger, at 1.64, even 
 when actual savings rates- which are twice as large for medium-sized farmsare assumed. This results from the stronger household consumption linkages 
 of medium -sized farms; as Hazell and Roell ( 1983) and Mellor and Lele ( 1973) 
 have noted, the PN coefficients for medium-sized farms are larger. 
 Before ending/deciding that farming-based development programs should target 
 medium -sized farms, some important qualifications need to be made. 
 First, the results assume that small- and medium-sized farms use the same 
 scale-free technology. This is often the case for HYV rice in much of Asia, but 
 where medium-sized farms are more mechanized, the extra employment they 
 create in the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things) might be offset by losses in direct employment in farming. Second, by holding investment constant, the model 
 does not allow for possible differences in the nontradable content of investment expense by farm size group. The difference in the multipliers could 
 be worn away if small farms invest greater shares of their savings locally than their 
 medium-sized brothers. Third, the results are sensitive to the assumed supply 
 elasticities in the model. If nontradables are less elastic in supply, or if the 
 export demand for the area's tradables were inelastic, then the relative size 
 of the multipliers might be reduced or reversed. 
 The choice between targeting huge houses or smallholders in Africa and Latin 
 America is less confusing. The huge houses create smaller multipliers if, as seems 
 reasonable, they have crowded household expense patterns with low not important budget shares for (away from cities) nontradables. Only if their expense patterns 
 approach those of smaller-sized farms do the huge houses create more good 
 multipliers. 
 A comparison of traditional and high cooperating with/producing/giving up varieties on Asian rice farms 
 shows a larger multiplier for the HYVs ( 1.56 against/compared to/or 1.38). Farms growing traditional varieties require fewer tradable inputs, and their ratios of value added 
 
 360 
 
 to gross output are higher. But this positive (thing that's given/work that's done) toward the multiplier 
 is more than offset by lower household demand linkages as a result of lower 
 incomes and smaller not important budget shares for nontradables. 
 The choice of mechanization package (oxen against/compared to/or tractors) does not affect 
 the multiplier on Asian rice farms, although oxen (producing crops/helping something grow) does produce 
 higher indirect income small steps forward/upward than hoe (producing crops/helping something grow) among Africa's 
 smallholders. Greater mechanization increases the demand for nontradable 
 intermediates in production (iron workering, machinery repair and servicing, 
 etc.), and this adds to the size of the multiplier. At the same time, there is an 
 almost exactly offsetting effect due to a decline in the value added created 
 per unit of output. The size of the multiplier therefore depends on the strength 
 of the household demand linkages. If mechanization leads to increased family 
 incomes, and because of this larger not important budget shares for nontradables, the multiplier is larger. This seems to be the case with oxen (producing crops/helping something grow) in Africa, because it enables farmers to help grow more land. But if mechanization simply 
 involves a substitution of capital for labor without adding/giving much to total 
 income- as is often the case with tractors in Asia (World Bank, 1987) -the 
 multiplier is no larger than for less mechanized technologies. 
 5. Ends/end results 
 (related to computers and science) advance in farming creates big increases in (away from cities) income over and above the direct hit/effect on farming-based earnings. These 
 benefits are of the order of 25 and 75 cents for each $1.00 of value added created directly in farming. 
 Because consumption linkages account for over 80% of the indirect income 
 small steps forward/upward, the most important features of farming-based technology are those 
 affecting income distribution and because of this consumption patterns. Input divisibility comes out as most important because of the prospects it offers for (existing all over a large area) distribution across income classes. In general, this hints that (related to the body function of living things) improvements will produce greater indirect income benefits than will 
 mechanical inventions of new things. Middle-sized farms appear to create the greatest 
 (away from cities) growth linkages because of greater demand (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into nonfarm 
 products (that are bought and sold)  compared to small farms and because of lower import content than estate farms, although this final guess will require confirmation once careful 
 large-farm consumption profiles become available. 
 Through the labor market, farming-based growth also influences (away from cities) wage 
 rates and so the supply side of the (away from cities) nonfarm (process of people making, selling, and buying things). Scientific studies suggest that labor-using farming-based growth can effectively help develop a move 
 to high-return nonfarm activities. 
 While the type of (related to computers and science) change influences the relative size of the 
 multiplier, its total size is mostly controlled by the policy, institutional and 
 useful thing/valuable supply (surrounding conditions) in which farming-based production happens. The mul- 
 
 361 
 
 tipliers tend to be smaller in Africa, for example, probably as a reflection of 
 poorer (away from cities) (set of machines), lower population density, lower income and as a result less personal (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) into nonfoods, fewer prospects for crop-watering/rinsing with water and therefore fewer backward linkages than other areas. Because 
 appropriate public policies and investments will play an important in improving 
 the strength of the indirect benefits of farming-based growth, they should be seen 
 as playing a (completing/matching) role to investments in farming-based research. 
 
